{"id":4465,"global_id":"www.unitingnc.org?id=4465","global_id_lineage":["www.unitingnc.org?id=4465"],"author":"25","status":"publish","date":"2018-10-10 13:27:20","date_utc":"2018-10-10 17:27:20","modified":"2018-10-10 13:27:20","modified_utc":"2018-10-10 17:27:20","url":"https:\/\/www.unitingnc.org\/stand-with-us\/october-12-bisbee-17-w-live-qa-with-director-robert-greene-raleigh\/","rest_url":"https:\/\/www.unitingnc.org\/wp-json\/tribe\/events\/v1\/events\/4465","title":"October 12: Bisbee 17&#8242; w\/ Live Q&#038;A with Director Robert Greene (Raleigh)","description":"<p>An old mining town on the Arizona-Mexico border finally reckons with its darkest day: the deportation of 1200 immigrant miners exactly 100 years ago. Locals collaborate to stage recreations of their controversial past.<\/p>\n<p>Opening night &#8211; featuring a live Q&amp;A w\/ Director Robert Greene (NCSU \u201900) moderated by Ana Pardo, Policy Advocate for the NC Justice Center\u2019s Workers\u2019 Rights Project.<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;Even though &#8220;Bisbee &#8217;17&#8221; depicts a wholesome and harmonious community undertaking, it is a profoundly haunted and haunting film.&#8221; &#8211; A.O. Scott, New York Times &#8211; Critic&#8217;s Pick<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;The result is a singularly American riff on The Act of Killing, a fascinating and dream-like mosaic that&#8217;s less driven by residual anger than by cockeyed concern, less interested in exhuming the past than in revealing its value to the present.&#8221; &#8211; David Ehrlich, IndieWire<\/p>\n<p>&#8220;Remembering the past is not enough to prevent its recurrence. It has to be kept alive.&#8221; &#8211; Sam Adams, Slate<\/p>","excerpt":"<a href=\"\" class=\"more-link\" title=\"Read More\">Read More<\/a>","slug":"october-12-bisbee-17-w-live-qa-with-director-robert-greene-raleigh","image":{"url":"https:\/\/www.unitingnc.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/43522999_2170927379834025_9142312345983254528_n.jpg","id":4466,"extension":"jpg","wi